# CS 300 – Data Structures and Algorithms

### What was the problem you were solving in the projects for this course?

In this course, I was tasked with designing and implementing a system to manage and display Computer Science course data efficiently. The projects required storing course information, sorting courses alphanumerically, 
and retrieving prerequisite data for individual courses. The primary challenge was determining which data structures best supported these operations while balancing runtime performance, memory usage, and maintainability. 
Beyond producing functional code, I was required to analyze how different data structures impact efficiency and scalability.

### How did you approach the problem? Consider why data structures are important to understand.

I approached the problem by first reviewing the functional requirements and then evaluating multiple data structures—vectors, hash tables, and binary search trees—to determine their strengths and weaknesses for the given 
use cases. Data structures are foundational because they directly influence algorithmic efficiency, data access speed, and overall system performance. By comparing insertion, search, and sorting behaviors, I was able to 
make informed decisions rather than defaulting to a single structure. This ensured that my solutions were efficient and aligned with best practices in software design.

### How did you overcome any roadblocks you encountered while going through the activities or project?

One significant challenge was correctly handling prerequisite relationships while maintaining sorted output. I addressed this by breaking the problem into smaller, manageable steps and using pseudocode to outline logic 
beforeimplementation. I also relied on structured testing and incremental debugging to validate data loading, sorting, and retrieval. Runtime analysis helped identify inefficiencies, allowing me to refine my approach 
and improve program correctness and performance.

### How has your work on this project expanded your approach to designing software and developing programs?

This project strengthened my design-first mindset. I now place greater emphasis on analyzing requirements and selecting appropriate data structures before writing code. The experience reinforced the importance of scalability
and efficiency, especially when working with growing datasets. These skills translate directly to real-world software development, where thoughtful design decisions reduce technical debt and improve long-term maintainability.

### How has your work on this project evolved the way you write programs that are maintainable, readable, and adaptable?

Through this course, I have improved how I structure and document my code. I consistently use clear naming conventions, modular functions, and logical separation of concerns. Evaluating multiple data structures also taught me
how to adapt solutions when requirements change. As a result, my programs are easier to read, maintain, and extend—qualities that are essential for collaborative and professional software development.
